<span id="freeTextContainer17317719906063491604">(4.5) A Midwestern Gothic? A Midwestern Gothic!<br/><br/>This is a very slow-paced, very atmospheric story, drawing on the long traditions of small town families and Old English folklore (think: Montagues &amp; Capulets meet Beowulf in Nowhere, MN). Definitely a good book to get me into a spooky October reading kind of mood, but also an all-around well written and enjoyable story. I&apos;m reminded a bit of &quot;Drive Your Plow Over the Bones of the Dead&quot; by Olga Tokarczuk, though I&apos;ve enjoyed Little Wolves so much mo</span>
  <span id="freeText17317719906063491604" style="display:none">(4.5) A Midwestern Gothic? A Midwestern Gothic!<br /><br />This is a very slow-paced, very atmospheric story, drawing on the long traditions of small town families and Old English folklore (think: Montagues &amp; Capulets meet Beowulf in Nowhere, MN). Definitely a good book to get me into a spooky October reading kind of mood, but also an all-around well written and enjoyable story. I'm reminded a bit of "Drive Your Plow Over the Bones of the Dead" by Olga Tokarczuk, though I've enjoyed Little Wolves so much more. There's just something so hauntingly enchanting about Clara and Grizz's (and Seth's) stories; it's difficult to look away from them, and difficult to not empathize too. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17317719906063491604" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


