<div id="review_497380920" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/497380920" />
    <a title="Tracey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858840-tracey"><img alt="Tracey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1340024531p2/5858840.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/497380920?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tracey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tracey" href="/user/show/5858840-tracey">Tracey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer497380920" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11188910206508495273">Not a narrative that would normally pull me in, but this one did and I very much enjoyed it. It reminded a bit of The Story of Edgar Sawtelle in terms of the setting, characters, and of course the characters&apos; relationship with the coyotes/dogs. I think the back story of the two crazy a## sheriffs could have used a little more development, but maybe it&apos;s okay to wonder what set them down that path. Maltman&apos;s writing style is swift, concise, and powerfully descriptive without being overly verbose.</span>
  <span id="freeText11188910206508495273" style="display:none">Not a narrative that would normally pull me in, but this one did and I very much enjoyed it. It reminded a bit of The Story of Edgar Sawtelle in terms of the setting, characters, and of course the characters' relationship with the coyotes/dogs. I think the back story of the two crazy a## sheriffs could have used a little more development, but maybe it's okay to wonder what set them down that path. Maltman's writing style is swift, concise, and powerfully descriptive without being overly verbose...my favorite!</span>
  <a data-text-id="11188910206508495273" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


